broad general rule applying to all electromagnetic forces, and (2) Coulomb's law - the fundamental law of electrostatics. From these, all else followed. You may have noticed, in studying the exercises in this chapter, that the electric field always undergoes a discontinuity when you cross a surface charge σ \sigma σ . In fact, it is a simple matter to find the amount by which E changes at such a boundary. Suppose we draw a wafer-thin Gaussian pillbox, extending just barely over the edge in each direction (Fig. 2.36). Gauss's law says that ∮ S E ⋅ d a = 1 ϵ 0 Q e n c = 1 ϵ 0 σ A \oint _{S} \vec{E} \cdot \dd{\vec{a}} =  rac{1}{\epsilon_0} Q_{enc} =  rac{1}{\epsilon_0} \sigma A ∮ S ​ E ⋅ d a = ϵ 0 ​ 1 ​ Q e n c ​ = ϵ 0 ​ 1 ​ σ A where A is the area of the pillbox lid. If σ \sigma σ varies from point to point or the surface is curved, we can simply pick A to be extremely small. Now, the sides of the pillbox contribute nothing to the flux, in the limit as the thickness ϵ \epsilon ϵ goes to zero, so we are left with E a b o v e ⊥ − E b e l o w ⊥ = 1 ϵ 0 σ 2.31 (2.31) E_{above}^{\perp} - E_{below} ^{\perp} =  rac{1}{\epsilon_0} \sigma \label{2.31} 	ag{2.31} E a b o v e ⊥ ​ − E b e l o w ⊥ ​ = ϵ 0 ​ 1 ​ σ 2 . 3 1 ( 2 . 3 1 ) where E a b o v e ⊥ E_{above}^{\perp} E a b o v e ⊥ ​ denotes the component of E \vec{E} E that is perpendicular to the surface immediately above, and E b e l o w ⊥ E_{below} ^{\perp} E b e l o w ⊥ ​ is the same, only just below the surface. For consistency, let "upward" be the positive direction for both. Conclusion: the normal component of E \vec{E} E is discontinuous by an amount σ / ϵ 0 \sigma / \epsilon_0 σ / ϵ 0 ​ at any boundary. In particular, where there is no surface charge, E ⊥ \vec{E}^{\perp} E ⊥ is continuous, as for instance at the surface of a uniformly charged solid sphere. The tangential component of E \vec{E} E , by contrast, is always continuous. For if we apply Eq. 2.19, ∮ E ⋅ d l = 0 \oint \vec{E} \cdot \dd{\vec{l}} = 0 ∮ E ⋅ d l = 